Also, the surface  is timelike in the Lorentzian section, but, at the moment of this writing, we
do not know either, if, and how, the results of this article are related to discussions
in terms of asymptotia in time (see, for example, and).

Quite independently of the above issues, which manifest themselves in the presence
of rotation, we should emphasize that the consideration of a black hole in de Sitter
space leads naturally, as a particular case, to define the energy and angular momentum
of de Sitter space by removing the line , corresponding to the worldline of a geodesic observer.
Both  and  vanish in this case. One may apply to de Sitter space with the line
 removed a general de Sitter transformation. One would obtain then, again,
a de Sitter space, but with the line  of another de Sitter coordinate system removed.
This would be a different space which would also have . In that sense
one might say that the "vacuum" is degenerate. Again,  it is beyond the scope of this paper to
attempt to relate these elementary comments to the ample existing literature on de Sitter
vacua.

Thermodynamics 


If one fixes the energy and the angular momentum, one is dealing with the microcanonical
ensemble in thermodynamics. In the semiclassical approximation, the value of the
action in that ensemble gives the entropy. An important advantage of using the Hamiltonian action,
as we have done in this paper, is that the bulk term given by Eq. ()
vanishes on-shell for a stationary solution, such as the Kerr-de Sitter metric.
Therefore, one finds from () the expected result,
 
for the entropy .
One may also use the canonical ensemble, in which case one adds to the action the term
, where the inverse temperature  is now held fixed. If one demands this
new action (which is the negative of the Helmholtz free energy) to have an extremum under
variations of , one finds the standard thermodynamical result
 
which combined with Eq. () gives
 
and therefore fixes the time period. It is important to
clarify here the geometrical meaning of the time . Indeed, in asymptotically
flat space one is satisfied with the relation () between the temperature and the
Euclidean time , because one has assumed that the lapse function  tends to
unity at infinity. Here, Eq. () holds with the standard form of the Kerr-de Sitter metric,
written in Appendix A, for which the rescaled lapse function,
 
introduced in Appendix B, is set equal to unity at the horizon. A similar rescaling
of the lapse function comes in anti-de Sitter space. In all three cases, the time 
is the "Killing time". In asymptotically flat space  coincides with the proper time displacement but
in the de Sitter case it does not coincide with the proper angle  introduced in Eq. (),
 and, in anti-de Sitter,  it does not coincide with the hyperbolic analog of .


